The '''Perijá tapaculo''' ('''''Scytalopus perijanus''''') is a [[species]] of [[passerine]] bird in the [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Tapaculo|Rhinocryptidae]] (tapaculos). [[Endemism|Endemic]] to the [[Serranía del Perijá]] mountain range on the [[Colombia]]–[[Venezuela]] border, the Perijá tapaculo is found at altitudes of {{convert|1600|-|3225|m|abbr=off|-2}}. Its body is {{convert|10|to|12|cm|abbr=off}} long and its tail is about {{convert|4|cm|abbr=on}} long. Specimens have long been stored in museums, but the species was [[species description|described]] only in 2015 based on sixteen specimens found between July 2008 and February 2009. It is considered vulnerable to extinction.

Adults have neutral grey heads, brown necks, brown-[[sepia (color)|sepia]] striped backs, and grey-white bellies, breasts, and throats. Males have some [[buff (colour)|buff]] markings on their breasts, and less sharp brown spots on their napes than females. The Perijá tapaculo is a secretive bird and therefore difficult to observe; as a result its ecology is poorly known. It feeds on insects and reproduces between April and July. Its range is partially within [[Chamicero de Perijá Bird Reserve]] in Colombia and the [[Sierra de Perijá National Park]] in Venezuela.

==Taxonomy==
[[Tapaculo]]s are the most primitive family of [[Tyranni|suboscines]], divided into 12 genera containing 60 species.<ref name="HBW-tapaculo">{{cite book|last1=Krabbe|first1=N.K.|last2=Schulenberg|first2=T.S|editor-last1=del Hoyo|editor-first1=J.|editor-last2=Elliott|editor-first2=A.|editor-last3=Sargatal|editor-first3=J.|editor-last4=Christie|editor-first4=D.A.|editor-last5=de Juana|editor-first5=E.|chapter-url=http://www.hbw.com/family/tapaculos-rhinocryptidae|chapter=Tapaculos (''Rhinocryptidae'')|title=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive|publisher=Lynx Edicions|location=Barcelona|year=2020|doi=10.2173/bow.rhinoc1.01|s2cid=243247124|access-date=1 October 2015|chapter-url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414183947/http://www.hbw.com/family/tapaculos-rhinocryptidae|archive-date=14 April 2015}}</ref> ''Scytalopus'', the genus to which the Perijá tapaculo belongs, has an abundance of similar species, many of which are difficult to classify through appearance.<ref name="HBW-tapaculo"/> Some individual species from other genera are like ''Scytalopus'' in size and plumage, but have different behaviour and [[Morphology (biology)|morphological]] features. Vocal studies and [[mitochondrial DNA]] analysis are often used to differentiate between species within the genus; a number of visually identical species previously classified as [[subspecies]] of the [[Magellanic tapaculo]] (''S. magellanicus'') have been identified through these methods, and the majority of subspecies within the genus have subsequently been reclassified as separate species.<ref name="HBW-tapaculo"/>

Between 1941 and 1942, American [[ornithology|ornithologist]] [[Melbourne Armstrong Carriker]] collected 27 specimens of the Perijá tapaculo in six locations on the western side of the [[Serranía del Perijá]]. He identified them as specimens of the [[white-crowned tapaculo]] (''S.&nbsp;atratus''), despite size and colour differences, and sent them to the [[National Museum of Natural History]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=451}} In 1953, the specimens began to attract the attention of biologists, and were successively identified as the [[brown-rumped tapaculo]] (''S.&nbsp;latebricola''), the [[Caracas tapaculo]] (''S.&nbsp;caracae''), and the [[Mérida tapaculo]] (''S.&nbsp;meridanus'').{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=451}} Some further believed that the specimens could belong to an undescribed species, or constitute a subspecies of the [[pale-bellied tapaculo]] (''S.&nbsp;griseicollis'') or the Mérida tapaculo based on morphological studies,{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=451}} but they were never classified as any of these.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=C98B936330D30636|title=''Scytalopus perijanus''|publisher=Avibase|date=March 2015|access-date=1 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002185014/http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=C98B936330D30636|archive-date=2 October 2015}}</ref>

In September 2006, biologists [[Juan Pablo López (biologist)|Juan Pablo López]] and [[Alexander Cortés Diago]] found two specimens in a [[cloud forest]] at an altitude of {{convert|2450|m|ft|abbr=on|-2}} on the western side of the Serranía del Perijá in Colombia, but the information collected was insufficient to identify a new species.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=451}} Between July 2008 and February 2009, sixteen new specimens were collected in an area previously explored by Carriker. New vocal, morphological, genetic, and ecological studies of these specimens confirmed that they constituted a new species, ''Scytalopus perijanus'',{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=451}} first [[species description|described]] by [[Jorge Enrique Avendaño]] et al. on 11 March 2015{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|pp=450–451}} following a three-year expedition,<ref name="Audubon">{{cite news|first=Jesse|last=Greenspan|url=https://www.audubon.org/news/new-south-american-bird-species-discovered-old-museum-drawer|title=New South American Bird Species Discovered in Old Museum Drawer|publisher=[[National Audubon Society]]|date=31 March 2015|access-date=25 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926022243/https://www.audubon.org/news/new-south-american-bird-species-discovered-old-museum-drawer|archive-date=26 September 2015}}</ref> and accepted by the [[American Ornithologists' Union#Committees|South American Classification Committee]].<ref name="SACC">{{cite web|url=http://www.museum.lsu.edu/~Remsen/SACCprop670.htm|title=Recognize ''Scytalopus perijanus'' as a valid species (Proposal 670)|publisher=[[American Ornithologists' Union#Committees|South American Classification Committee]]|date=March 2015|access-date=25 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919034615/http://www.museum.lsu.edu/~Remsen/SACCprop670.htm|archive-date=19 September 2015}}</ref> The Latin word ''perijanus'' refers to the Serranía del Perijá mountain range,{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=455}} and the genus name ''Scytalopus'' comes from the Greek ''skutale'' (stick) and ''pous'' (foot).<ref>{{cite book | last= Jobling | first= James A. | year= 2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | publisher = A & C Black | location = London | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 |page = 352}}</ref>

The [[Type (biology)|type specimen]] of the Perijá tapaculo, an adult male, was found in the Serranía del Perijá near the El Cinco [[vereda]] of [[Manaure, Cesar|Manaure]], [[Cesar Department]], Colombia, at an altitude of {{convert|2450|m|abbr=on|-2}}.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=451}} Avendaño lured the specimen by playing a recording of its song on 10 July 2008 at the edge of a [[Montane ecology#Montane forests|montane forest]].{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=451}} Sequence analysis of the mitochondrial gene [[MT-ND2|ND2]] from the Perijá tapaculo showed that its nearest relatives are the brown-rumped tapaculo, Caracas tapaculo, and Mérida tapaculo.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|pp=456–457}}

==Description==
[[File:Scytalopus perijanus (16601135579).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|left|A juvenile specimen of the Perijá tapaculo|alt=Image showing a juvenile Perijá tapaculo]]
The Perijá tapaculo is a small bird, {{convert|10|to|12|cm|abbr=on}} in length with an average mass of 17 to 18 grams (about 0.6 oz).{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=452}} The bill averages {{convert|6.8|mm|abbr=off}} long, {{convert|2.9|mm|abbr=on}} wide, and {{convert|3.5|mm|abbr=on}} high.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=452}} The legs are about {{convert|21|mm|abbr=on}} long. The Perijá tapaculo's [[tarsometatarsus|tarsus]] averages {{convert|21.1|mm}} long.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=452}} The wings measure {{convert|57.4|mm|abbr=on}} on average and the tail is about {{convert|40|mm|abbr=on}} long{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=452}} with between 8 and 12 [[Flight feather#Rectrices|rectrices]].{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=456}}

The forehead, [[Lore (anatomy)|lores]], crown, mantle, and [[scapula]]r area are a neutral grey colour. There is a brown spot on the nape. The top of the tail is brown, and the bottom is faintly striped brown. The bird's back and rump are striped brown-[[Sepia (color)|sepia]], and the throat, breast, and belly are grey-white. Its lower belly and flanks are [[Tawny (color)|tawny]].{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=452}} The [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]] is dark brown. Male specimens are distinguished by having less sharp brown spots on their napes, and the bottom of their breasts are mixed with a pale [[Buff (colour)|buff]] colour. The legs are brown on the back and whitish on the front. Young birds have a yellowish appearance with striped brown flanks.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=452}}

The bird's plumage colouration is most similar to the pale-bellied tapaculo.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=452}} The ''S. g. morenoi'' subspecies of the pale-bellied tapaculo can be differentiated from the Perijá tapaculo by its entirely brown back and nape, and its different calls. Juveniles of this subspecies have a dull [[Anatomical terms of location#Dorsal and ventral|ventral]] plumage, while the Perijá tapaculo has a more yellow plumage.{{sfn|Avendaño|Donegan|2015|p=139}} It also resembles the Caracas tapaculo but has a duller ventral colour.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=452}}

==Ecology and behaviour==
[[File:Song and Call of Perijá Tapaculo (Scytalopus perijanus)-SD.ogg|thumb|right|Song and call]]
Like other species in genus ''[[Scytalopus]]'', the Perijá tapaculo is secretive and therefore difficult to observe.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=460}} The call and song differ from those of most other species in the genus, and the latter is composed of two short ''churr''s repeating up to 65 times at 0.5 to 3&nbsp;second intervals.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=452}} The diet of the species is little known, but studies of the stomach contents of seven specimens suggested that they fed exclusively on insects.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=460}}

Little is known about the reproduction of the species, but it is believed to nest between April and July.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=460}} The species builds its [[wikt:globular|globular]] nests in underground cavities about {{convert|12|cm|abbr=on}} in diameter and about {{convert|14.5|cm|abbr=on}} in height, lined with mosses, grasses, and plant roots around a central space about {{convert|9|cm|abbr=on}} wide. The nests are accessed by a short tunnel with a depth of {{convert|10|cm|abbr=on}} and a diameter of {{convert|4.2|cm|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=460}} Young birds may leave the nest at the end of June. Like those of other ''Scytalopus'' species, male specimens have demonstrated involvement in parenting.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=460}}

==Distribution and habitat==
<!--{{Location map | Colombia|relief = yes|lat_deg = 10.016389|lon_deg = -72.957778|mark = Map pointer.svg|marksize = 12|caption = Geographical distribution of ''Scytalopus perijanus''|alt = Map showing the geographical distribution of Scytalopus perijanus shown by a pointer}}-->
[[File:El Cinco, Serranía de Perijá, Cesar, Colombia (15448520209).jpg|thumb|left|The Serranía del Perijá mountain range near the El Cinco vereda in Colombia, where the type specimen was collected|alt=Mountain range Serranía del Perijá]]
The Perijá tapaculo is [[endemism|endemic]] to the Serranía del Perijá,{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=451}} a mountain range on the Colombia–Venezuela border known for its high rates of endemism.<ref name="Watsa">{{cite news|url=http://news.mongabay.com/2015/05/new-bird-uncovered-in-south-american-conflict-region-researchers-urge-protection/|first=Mrinalini Erkenswick|last=Watsa|title=New bird uncovered in South American conflict region, researchers urge protection|publisher=[[Mongabay]]|date=28 May 2015|access-date=1 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Serranía del Perijá|url = http://www.amphibians.org/explore/projects/south-america/serrania-del-perija/|access-date=20 August 2015|year=2014|publisher = Amphibian Specialist Group and Amphibian Survival Alliance|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914112904/http://www.amphibians.org/explore/projects/south-america/serrania-del-perija/|archive-date=14 September 2015}}</ref> It has been observed in nineteen localities on both sides of the border between altitudes of {{convert|1600|and|3225|m|ft|abbr=on|-2}} above sea level; in its northern range, there are no suitable forests below {{convert|1600|m|ft|abbr=on|-2}}.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|pp=458–459}} The bird has been observed at {{convert|1800|-|3120|m|ft|abbr=on|-2}} on the Venezuelan side, and at 1,600{{Endash}}3,225&nbsp;m on the Colombian side.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|pp=458–459}}

The Perijá tapaculo lives in and on the edges of humid [[rainforest]]s, as well as in [[elfin forest]]s and amongst woody ''[[páramo]]'' shrubs in high-mountain grassland areas, especially at altitudes of {{convert|2500|-|3000|m|ft|abbr=on|-2}}.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=460}} Some specimens have been observed feeding in dense thickets within {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} of the ground, often near the forest. Others have been observed running among bushes through open grassy areas.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=460}}

The species has not been identified as being [[sympatric]] with any other species of the genus ''Scytalopus''.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|pp=458–459}} However, there is a possibility that its range overlaps with that of the ''S.&nbsp;atratus&nbsp;nigricans'', which occupies a different micro-habitat on the eastern side of the Serranía del Perijá at altitudes of {{convert|1500|-|1900|m|ft|abbr=on|-2}}; or that it may be found within the range of the [[pale-bellied tapaculo]] in the lower reaches of the [[Serranía de Los Motilones]] mountain range, south of the Serranía del Perijá.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|pp=458–459}}

==Threats and protection==
Avendaño et al. wrote in the original description of the Perijá tapaculo that the size and quality of the species' range are being reduced, although it can tolerate a certain level of [[Disjunct distribution|fragmentation]] of its range. Its natural habitat covers about {{convert|5000|sqkm|sqmi}}.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=462}} The description entails the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) classification of this species as near threatened.<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> The authors believe that to protect the Perijá tapaculo, conservation measures on the Colombian side of the border should be implemented, as the forests of the Serranía del Perijá have been largely destroyed on the Colombian side by [[logging]] activities and forest clearance for agriculture.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=462}}

On 28 January 2014, prior to the formal description of the bird, the [[Chamicero de Perijá Bird Reserve]] was created by [[Fundación ProAves]] to maintain one of Colombia's most fragile habitats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proaves.org/chamicero-del-perija-lodge-reserva/|title=Reserva Chamicero del Perijá|trans-title=Chamicero del Perijá Reserve|language=es|publisher=Fundación ProAves|date=28 January 2014|access-date=1 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906103714/http://www.proaves.org/chamicero-del-perija-lodge-reserva/|archive-date=6 September 2015}}</ref> In addition to the Perijá tapaculo, several other Perijá-endemic endangered species, such as the [[Perijá metaltail]] (''Metallura iracunda'') and [[Perijá thistletail]] (''Asthenes perijana'') are protected within this reserve's {{convert|749|ha}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proaves.org/reserva-chamicero-del-perija-de-proaves-protege-nueva-especie-de-tapaculo-2/|title=Reserva Chamicero del Perijá de ProAves protege nueva especie de Tapaculo|work=Fundación ProAves - por la conservación en el país de las aves |trans-title=Chamicero Perija ProAves Reserve protects new species of Tapaculo|language=es|publisher=Fundación ProAves|date=7 May 2015|access-date=1 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907234958/http://www.proaves.org/reserva-chamicero-del-perija-de-proaves-protege-nueva-especie-de-tapaculo-2/|archive-date=7 September 2015 |author1=Dogie_To }}</ref> The Colombian section of the Serranía del Perijá is dangerous for scientific excursions due to the presence of the [[FARC]] [[guerrilla warfare|guerrilla group]] in the region.<ref name="Watsa"/> In Venezuela, the [[Sierra de Perijá National Park]] covers {{convert|300000|ha}} and partially protects the habitat of the Perijá tapaculo.{{sfn|Avendaño et al.|2015|p=462}}

